Plotly foresaw a need for someone like myself to build interactive visualizations within Shiny.

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:22.160
So, they provided the functions needed to do that. That ability to drag and drop those plot points

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:28.880
is because of the Plotly function. Within Shiny, there's also this concept of reactivity.

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:34.479
This is another key feature that made this app work. More specifically, we used a combination

00:19:34.479 --> 00:19:39.439
of something called reactive list, reactive functions, and event observations. These three

00:19:39.439 --> 00:19:45.199
taken together made it possible for us to see that the end user was moving those individual

00:19:45.199 --> 00:19:51.760
model inputs and then reacting and rewriting the new data to serve as the model inputs later.

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:55.439
I can actually show you a little bit more of what I mean by that.

00:19:57.040 --> 00:20:03.760
So, if you see here, we have the app that I showed you earlier. And let me think of the

00:20:03.760 --> 00:20:11.680
best way to do this. All right. So, now we can go to the actual app script. That's what this is.

00:20:11.680 --> 00:20:18.319
It's app.r. What you see here was generated by the code here. And for those who don't know,

00:20:18.319 --> 00:20:25.040
there's a few components to a Shiny app. You have your UI object. This is like the skeleton of the

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:30.719
application. This determines where this table and this table go and also determines why you can

00:20:30.719 --> 00:20:37.199
toggle back and forth between these two input methods. Then there's the server object. This

00:20:37.199 --> 00:20:41.599
is where most of the actual coding and logic goes to support the functionality. It's where we

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:46.319
actually generate the plot. If you look here, we have a render plotly function.

00:20:46.880 --> 00:20:53.359
And within that, we actually have the actual plotly function itself, which produces this plot.

00:20:55.280 --> 00:21:01.920
Now, UI and server, those are the two common, I guess you would call them objects. But there's

00:21:01.920 --> 00:21:09.599
also global objects. And what you see up here is this matrix, which are the default values used.

00:21:09.599 --> 00:21:13.760
So, whenever we open this application, we actually see these original values here.

00:21:14.319 --> 00:21:18.640
And no matter what we do, those original values are going to stay the same because it matches

00:21:18.640 --> 00:21:26.560
what is in this default matrix identified in the global settings. Now, normally, if we were making

00:21:26.560 --> 00:21:32.239
a shiny app that didn't require this interaction like we do, we could actually

00:21:33.439 --> 00:21:39.520
call upon that static data set in the global environment and pull it directly into the plotly

00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:45.439
one. And we would see those plot points just fine as it is. But because we want to give the ability

00:21:45.439 --> 00:21:50.880
for the end user to move those plot points and update a data set that feeds into the algorithm,

00:21:50.880 --> 00:21:55.520
we had to do a little bit more steps. And that's where this reactive values list comes in.

00:21:56.319 --> 00:22:01.680
Now, pay close attention to something here. If you look right here, it says 39 and 0.67.

00:22:02.319 --> 00:22:07.760
And over here in the reactive values, it says 39 and 0.67. When I move this plot point, I'm

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:13.599
going to move it to around 50 and 1. It stays the same in the original values, but it changes in the

00:22:13.599 --> 00:22:19.199
reactive values. That's because if we're going to do these kind of interactions, we have to both

00:22:19.199 --> 00:22:24.719
read reactive values and write to reactive values to make it work. And let me give you a broad

00:22:24.719 --> 00:22:30.079
overview of where that's at in the code. So, right above our render plotly function right here,

00:22:30.079 --> 00:22:38.560
we have a reactive values list. I just call it RV. And I pulled the values for time and speed

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:43.680
directly from that default matrix up above. That's why when you first open this app,

00:22:43.680 --> 00:22:51.680
the original values and the reactive values are the same. Next, we within let's see,

00:22:51.680 --> 00:22:56.640
within the render plotly function, we map those reactive values to the circles.

00:22:57.280 --> 00:23:04.880
And we also produce lines between them. In addition, we configure the plotly function

00:23:04.880 --> 00:23:10.239
to say we want the ability to do interactions with it. We want to be able to change the position of

00:23:10.239 --> 00:23:15.199
the shapes that are on there. And that's what those circles are. They're technically shapes.

00:23:15.920 --> 00:23:22.079
We also label this plotly function with the ID speed S. This is very important in the event

00:23:22.079 --> 00:23:28.160
tracking. So, all that data you see in here on this plot is not actually these original values.

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:31.680
They're the reactive values that have been copied from the original values.

00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:40.000
Further down below, we have the observe event function. What this does is I very specifically

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:45.599
told it to listen and keep an eye out on the end user on what they're doing. And if they happen to

00:23:45.599 --> 00:23:53.520
move a plotly point like they do, and that plot graph has the source of speed S, it's going to

00:23:53.520 --> 00:24:00.640
proceed with the script within that function. Right here, I won't walk you through these

00:24:00.640 --> 00:24:05.680
line by line, but basically what this does is it extracts the new coordinates. So, if I move this

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:13.359
to 60 and 0.8, the new coordinates are 50 or close to 60 and 0.8. Those are the new coordinates.

00:24:13.359 --> 00:24:18.800
And it extracts those from the event data. It enforces the rules on top of them, which you

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:25.119
see here, that 0 and 70. And it just rewrites it back to the reactive values list above.

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:31.839
So, it's basically becoming a circle. If I move this, it took the reactive values,

00:24:31.839 --> 00:24:36.079
gave it a new coordinates, and then it updated it back to the reactive value list.

00:24:36.719 --> 00:24:40.880
Same thing if I tried to move this. It takes the new values, makes sure it follows the rules. If

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:47.680
it doesn't, it moves it back and then updates the reactive values list. The shiny matrix,

00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:54.079
that's what allows this right here where we can hand type the inputs. It normally wouldn't need

00:24:54.079 --> 00:25:00.079
to be put inside an observe event function the way we do. This functionality actually works pretty

00:25:00.079 --> 00:25:04.160
good on its own that you don't have to do that. But because we had to make sure it follows the

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:10.959
same rules as the plotly graph and also because we had to make sure that we're syncing up these

00:25:10.959 --> 00:25:16.079
two input methods where if you change one on one, it needs to reflect on the other, we also had to

00:25:16.079 --> 00:25:20.479
pull it into an observe event function and apply those rules. But it's ultimately the same

00:25:20.479 --> 00:25:29.199
principles you're seeing there. But that's where did my PowerPoint slide go? It took me all the

